#chapter[Abbreviations and Reference Guide][Abbreviations]

The footnotes in this work follow the scholarly conventions of the
early eighteenth century, citing sources by abbreviated titles and
location markers that were familiar to educated readers of the time.
The following guide is provided for the modern reader's reference.
Scripture references follow standard English Bible abbreviations and
are not listed here.

== Latin Terms

/ 22ae.: _Secunda Secundae_ — the "Second Part of the Second Part" of Aquinas's _Summa Theologiae_; written as II-II in modern citations.
/ Advers.: _Adversus_ — "Against."
/ Apud: Latin for "found in" or "cited by."
/ Art.: _Articulus_ — Article; a subdivision within a formal theological question.
/ Can.: _Canon_ — a rule or decree of a church council.
/ Cap.: _Caput_ — Chapter.
/ Caus.: _Causa_ — Cause or Case; a section division in Gratian's _Decretum_.
/ Decret. / Decretal.: _Decretales_ — Decretals; authoritative papal rulings compiled into canon law.
/ Dist.: _Distinctio_ — Distinction; a division in Peter Lombard's _Sentences_ and the commentaries written on it.
/ Epist.: _Epistola_ — Letter.
/ Evang.: _Evangelium_ / _Evangelia_ — Gospel or Gospels.
/ Homil.: _Homilia_ — Homily.
/ Ibid.: _Ibidem_ — "in the same place"; refers to the immediately preceding source.
/ Lib.: _Liber_ — Book.
/ Loco sup. cit.: _Loco supra citato_ — "in the place cited above."
/ Qu. / qu.: _Quaestio_ — Question; a formal theological question in scholastic method.
/ Sent.: _Sententiae_ — the _Sentences_ of Peter Lombard (see below).
/ Ver.: _Versus_ — Verse; refers to a verse within the scripture passage most recently cited, rather than citing a new passage.

== Authors and Works

/ Thom. 22ae. qu. [N]. Art. [N].: Thomas Aquinas (1225–1274), _Summa Theologiae_, Part II-II (_Secunda Secundae_), Question [N], Article [N]. The definitive work of medieval Catholic theology, organized into questions and articles.

/ Bonavent. in lib. 4. Sent. Dist. [N]. Art. [N]. qu. [N].: Bonaventure (1221–1274), _Commentary on the Sentences of Peter Lombard_, Book 4, Distinction [N], Article [N], Question [N].

/ Lib. 4. Senten. Dist. [N]. / Lib. 4. Dist. [N]. qu. [N].: Peter Lombard (c. 1096–1160), _Sentences_ (_Sententiarum libri quatuor_), Book 4, Distinction [N]. The standard theological textbook of medieval universities. Aquinas, Bonaventure, and nearly every major scholastic theologian wrote commentaries on it, organized around the same Distinctions.

/ Bernard. Compost. / Bernar. Compostel.: Bernard of Compostella (13th century), _Commentary on the Decretals of Gregory IX_. Cited with a title and chapter, e.g., _De Simonia. cap. 1_ (On Simony, chapter 1).

/ Decret. Greg. 9. / Decretal. Gregor. 9.: _Decretals of Gregory IX_ (also called the _Liber Extra_, 1234) — the foundational collection of papal rulings in medieval canon law, compiled by Raymond of Peñafort at the order of Pope Gregory IX. It is divided into titled sections; those appearing in this work include: _De Simonia_ (On Simony), _De rerum permutatione_ (On the Exchange of Things), and _De Jure Patronatus_ (On the Right of Patronage).

/ Apud Gratian. Caus. [N]. Qu. [N]. Can. [title]: Gratian (12th century), _Decretum_ (_Concordia Discordantium Canonum_ — Harmony of Conflicting Canons, c. 1140) — the foundational text of medieval canon law. _Caus._ = Causa (a numbered case), _Qu._ = Question, _Can._ = the opening word or phrase of the canon cited.

/ Super Mattheum Homilia [N].: John Chrysostom (c. 349–407), _Homilies on Matthew_ (_In Matthaeum_), Homily [N].

/ In Rom. 1.: John Chrysostom, _Homilies on Romans_, Homily 1.

/ In Act 8: Nicolaus de Lyra (c. 1270–1349), _Postilla litteralis super totam Bibliam_ — a verse-by-verse commentary on the entire Bible. "In Act 8" refers to his commentary on Acts, chapter 8.

/ Greg. 7. Lib. [N]. Epist. [N].: Pope Gregory VII (c. 1015–1085), _Registrum_ (his collected letters), Book [N], Letter [N].

/ Homil. [N]. in Evang.: Gregory the Great (c. 540–604), _Homilies on the Gospels_ (_Homiliae in Evangelia_), Homily [N].

/ Pastor. Part. [N]. Cap. [N].: Gregory the Great, _Pastoral Rule_ (_Regula Pastoralis_), Part [N], Chapter [N]. A foundational guide to the duties and character of a bishop or pastor.

/ Lib. De past. cap. [N].: Augustine of Hippo (354–430), _On the Pastors_ (_De Pastoribus_), Chapter [N].

/ Advers. Jovin. Lib. [N].: Jerome (c. 345–420), _Against Jovinian_ (_Adversus Jovinianum_), Book [N].

/ Lib. De Dignit. Sacerdot. Cap. [N].: Attributed to Ambrose of Milan (c. 340–397), _On the Dignity of the Priesthood_ (_De Dignitate Sacerdotali_), Chapter [N].

/ Concil. Tolet. 4. Can. [N].: Fourth Council of Toledo (633 AD), Canon [N]. A Spanish church council notable for its canons on clerical discipline and the proper qualifications for ordination.

/ Append. Concil. Lateran. 3.: Appendix to the Third Lateran Council (1179 AD), an ecumenical council held in Rome under Pope Alexander III.

/ Can. [N]. Lib. 1. cap. [N]. (Second Aurelian Council): Second Council of Orléans (533 AD). Orléans was known in Latin as _Aurelia_, hence "Aurelian Council."

/ Epist. ad Johan. 22. in Concil. Tom. [N]. Part. [N].: Letter to Pope John XXII, cited from a published collection of council documents (_Conciliorum collectio_), Volume [N], Part [N].

/ Epist. [N]. Ad [Name].: Cyprian of Carthage (c. 200–258), _Letters_ (_Epistolae_), Letter [N], addressed to [Name]. Cyprian was an influential early bishop and martyr whose letters deal extensively with church discipline and authority.

/ De Eccles. Hier. Cap. [N].: Pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite (c. late 5th–early 6th century), _The Ecclesiastical Hierarchy_ (_De Ecclesiastica Hierarchia_), Chapter [N]. The work is attributed in the text to "Dionysius Areopagita," though the author acknowledges uncertainty ("or whosoever else is the author"). It is now recognized as the work of an anonymous Syrian writer writing in the Neoplatonist tradition.
